## Repository Structure
```
/
├── docs/
│   └── product-vision.md   # Shared product vision (source of truth)
├── .cursorrules            # This file
├── .gitignore              # Excludes .env files everywhere
├── README.md               # Repo overview
└── prototypes/
    ├── divya/              # Divya's individual prototype
    ├── shreeya/            # Shreeya's individual prototype
    ├── caroline/           # Caroline's individual prototype
    └── terry/              # Terry's individual prototype
```

Each prototype directory is independent — team members can use any stack they choose.

## Conventions (update as team decisions are made)
- Each prototype lives in prototypes/[yourname]/ and is self-contained
- Never commit .env files — use .env.example to document required variables
- Commit messages should be descriptive and reference what changed
- Each prototype must include: front end, back end, database, and at least one AI API integration

## AI Context & Constraints
- Core user problem: comparing grocery prices + distance across multiple local stores
- Key AI use case: matching equivalent products across stores from text or image input
- Users are budget-conscious shoppers; UX should minimize friction and be immediately useful
- Distance/travel tradeoff is a first-class feature, not an afterthought
- Be careful with equivalent product matching — dietary restrictions mean substitutions aren't always acceptable

## Tech Stack (to be updated as team decides)
- Stack per prototype is up to the individual at this stage
- AI API options: OpenAI, Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, etc.
- Consider: web scraping or store APIs for pricing, maps API for distance

## What Good Code Looks Like Here
- Suggestions should reflect the grocery price comparison domain
- API keys must always come from environment variables, never hardcoded
- Prototype bar is works on your laptop — prioritize clarity and speed over perfection
